  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Enhancing Sea Border Data Systems in South of Nigeria</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In 2016, IOM introduced the Migration Information and Data Analysis System (MIDAS) in Nigeria to strengthen the Federal Government of Nigeria&apos;s ability to process individuals&apos; identity when entering or exiting the country. This complex endeavour has been continuously supported by multiple donors and has contributed to the fortification of the country&apos;s border, especially in the north along the Niger borderline. The same cannot be said for the country&apos;s southern border shared with Cameroon as it has been experiencing a recent influx of driven by the Anglophone Crisis in northwest and south-west regions of Cameroon. Based on the achievements of the programme so far and to enhance the capacity of the Government to process migrants at its international borders in Akwa Ibom State, IOM in coordination with the Nigerian Immigration Service (NIS) will either install or repair and upgrade the MIDAS system at two strategically located seaports in the state as well as the State Command Office.</narrative>
  </description>
